That failure mode is plausible if the mutex protects only local execution, not the shared token/rate-limit state.

A mutex design can still fail when:

- The lock is created inside each request handler, controller instance, middleware instance, or worker object, so concurrent requests do not actually contend on the same lock.
- The service runs multiple Node processes, serverless instances, pods, or worker threads, each with its own in-memory mutex.
- Token state is keyed by tenant but the mutex is keyed by handler instance, route instance, user session object, or request context.
- The expired-token check happens before acquiring the mutex, and the code schedules refresh work before doing a second check inside the critical section.
- The mutex only wraps the refresh call but not the “observe expired → mark refresh in-flight” transition.
- Tenant state is stored in a shared cache/database, while the mutex is process-local, so two instances can both observe expired and both refresh.
- Dependency injection creates transient rate limiter instances rather than a singleton/shared per-tenant coordinator.

The specific bad shape is:

```ts
class Handler {
  private mutex = new Mutex();

  async handle(req) {
    if (tokenExpired(req.tenant)) {
      await this.mutex.runExclusive(() => refresh(req.tenant));
    }
  }
}
```

This only works if every concurrent request for that tenant reaches the same `Handler` object in the same process. If handlers are per-request or per-connection, the mutex is ineffective. If handlers are per-process but the service is horizontally scaled, it only prevents duplicates within one process.

A safer shape is usually a per-tenant single-flight registry:

```ts
const refreshesByTenant = new Map<string, Promise<Token>>();

async function refreshOnce(tenantId: string) {
  const existing = refreshesByTenant.get(tenantId);
  if (existing) return existing;

  const refresh = doRefresh(tenantId).finally(() => {
    refreshesByTenant.delete(tenantId);
  });

  refreshesByTenant.set(tenantId, refresh);
  return refresh;
}
```

That still needs process/distributed considerations if duplicate refresh across instances is unsafe. In that case, the coordination boundary must move to the shared state layer, for example a DB conditional update, Redis lock, lease row, or compare-and-swap on token version.
